# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: objective-c
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang operates in tandem with the LLVM compiler back end and has been a subproject of LLVM 2.6 and later.
[src:objective-c/clang] As with LLVM, it is free and open-source software under the Apache 2.0 software license.
[src:objective-c/clang] Its contributors include Apple, IBM, Microsoft, Google, ARM, Sony, Intel and AMD.
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang 22 has full support for all published C++ standards up to C++17, implements most features of C++20 and C++23, and has initial support for the C++26 standard.
[src:objective-c/clang] Since v16.0.0, Clang compiles C++ using the GNU++17 dialect by default, which includes features from the C++17 standard and conforming GNU extensions.
[src:objective-c/clang] In 2005, Apple Inc. made extensive use of LLVM in several commercial products, including the iOS SDK and Xcode 3.1.
[src:objective-c/clang] An OpenGL code compiler for OS X that converts OpenGL calls into more fundamental calls for graphics processing units (GPU) that do not support certain features was one of the first uses of LLVM.
[src:objective-c/clang] This enabled Apple to support OpenGL on computers using Intel GMA chipsets, increasing performance on those machines.
[src:objective-c/clang] The LLVM project originally intended to use GCC's front end.
[src:objective-c/clang] The GCC source code, however, is large and somewhat cumbersome; as one long-time GCC developer put it, referring to LLVM, "Trying to make the hippo dance is not really a lot of fun." Besides, Apple software uses Objective-C, which is a low priority for GCC developers.
[src:objective-c/clang] As such, GCC does not integrate smoothly into Apple's integrated development environment.
[src:objective-c/clang] Finally, GCC's license agreement, the GNU General Public License (GPL) version 3, requires developers who distribute extensions or modified versions of GCC to make their source code available, but LLVM's permissive software license doesn't require this.
[src:objective-c/clang] For these reasons, Apple developed Clang, a new compiler front end which supports C, Objective-C and C++.
[src:objective-c/clang] In July 2007, the project received the approval for becoming open-source.
[src:objective-c/clang] The combination of Clang and LLVM provides most of the toolchain for replacing the GCC stack.
[src:objective-c/clang] One of Clang's main goals is to provide a library-based architecture, so that the compiler could interoperate with other tools that interact with source code, such as integrated development environments (IDE).
[src:objective-c/clang] In contrast, GCC works in a compile-link-debug workflow; integrating it with other tools is not always easy.
[src:objective-c/clang] For instance, GCC uses a step called *fold* that is key to the overall compile process, which has the side effect of translating the code tree into a form that looks unlike the original source code.
[src:objective-c/clang] If an error is found during or after the fold step, it can be difficult to translate that back into one location in the original source.
[src:objective-c/clang] Besides, vendors using the GCC stack within IDEs must use separate tools to index the code, to provide features like syntax highlighting and intelligent code completion.
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang retains more information during the compiling process than GCC, and preserves the overall form of the original code, making it easier to map errors back into the original source.
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang's error reports are more detailed, specific, and machine-readable, so IDEs can index the compiler's output.
[src:objective-c/clang] Modular design of the compiler can offer source code indexing, syntax checking, and other features normally associated with rapid application development systems.
[src:objective-c/clang] The parse tree is also more suitable for supporting automated code refactoring, as it directly represents the original source code.
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang compiles only C-like languages, such as C, C++, Objective-C, and Objective-C++.
[src:objective-c/clang] In many cases, Clang can replace GCC as needed, with no other effects on the toolchain as a whole.
[src:objective-c/clang] It supports most of the commonly used GCC options.
[src:objective-c/clang] A Fortran project, Flang was in-progress in 2022.
[src:objective-c/clang] However, for other languages, such as Ada, LLVM remains dependent on GCC or another compiler front end.
[src:objective-c/clang] The *Flang* project, by Nvidia and The Portland Group, adds Fortran support.
[src:objective-c/clang] Flang is LLVM's Fortran frontend, often referred to as *LLVM Flang* to differentiate it from *Classic Flang*.
[src:objective-c/clang] These are two separate and independent Fortran compilers.
[src:objective-c/clang] As of October 2023, development versions of Flang were in progress and could be downloaded from the LLVM Project.
[src:objective-c/clang] Its command-line interface shares many of GCC's flags and options.
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang implements many GNU language extensions and compiler intrinsics, some of which are purely for compatibility.
[src:objective-c/clang] For example, even though Clang implements atomic intrinsics which correspond exactly with C11 atomics, it also implements GCC's `__sync_*` intrinsics for compatibility with GCC and the C++ Standard Library (libstdc++).
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang also maintains application binary interface (ABI) compatibility with GCC-generated object code.
[src:objective-c/clang] In practice, Clang is a drop-in replacement for GCC.
[src:objective-c/clang] Clang's developers aim to reduce memory footprint and increase compiling speed compared to other compilers, such as GCC.
[src:objective-c/clang] In October 2007, they report that Clang compiled the Carbon libraries more than twice as fast as GCC, while using about one-sixth GCC's memory and disk space.
[src:objective-c/clang] By 2011, Clang seemed to retain this advantage in compiler performance.
[src:objective-c/clang] As of mid-2014, Clang still consistently compiles faster than GCC in a mixed compile time and program performance benchmark.
[src:objective-c/clang] However, by 2019, Clang is significantly slower at compiling the Linux Kernel than GCC while remaining slightly faster at compiling LLVM.
[src:objective-c/clang] While Clang has historically been faster than GCC at compiling, the output quality has lagged behind.
[src:objective-c/clang] As of 2014, performance of Clang-compiled programs lagged behind performance of the GCC-compiled program, sometimes by large factors (up to 5.5x), replicating earlier reports of slower performance.
[src:objective-c/clang] `libclang` provides a C interface, providing a relatively small API.
[src:objective-c/clang] Exposed functionality includes: parsing source code into an AST, loading ASTs, traversing the AST, associating source locations with elements within the AST.
[src:objective-c/clang] This table presents only significant steps and releases in Clang history.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of the Foundation Kit, Application Kit, and Core Data frameworks, as included by the `Cocoa.h` header file, and the libraries and frameworks included by those, such as the C standard library and the Objective-C runtime.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa applications are typically developed using the development tools provided by Apple, specifically Xcode (formerly Project Builder) and Interface Builder (now part of Xcode), using the programming languages Objective-C or Swift.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] However, the Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] It is also possible to write Objective-C Cocoa programs in a simple text editor and build it manually with GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or Clang from the command line or from a makefile.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] For end users, Cocoa applications are those written using the Cocoa programming environment.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Such applications usually have a familiar look and feel, since the Cocoa programming environment provides a lot of common UI elements (such as buttons, scroll bars, etc.), and automates many aspects of an application to comply with Apple's human interface guidelines.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] For iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, and watchOS, APIs similar to Application Kit, named UIKit and WatchKit, are available; they include gesture recognition, animation, and a different set of graphical control elements that are designed to accommodate the specific platforms they target.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit and Core Data are also available in those operating systems.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] It is used in applications for Apple devices such as the iPhone, the iPod Touch, the iPad, the Apple TV, and the Apple Watch.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa continues the lineage of several software frameworks (mainly the *App Kit* and *Foundation Kit*) from the NeXTSTEP and OpenStep programming environments developed by NeXT in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Apple acquired NeXT in December 1996, and subsequently went to work on the Rhapsody operating system that was to be the direct successor of OPENSTEP.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] It was to have had an emulation base for classic Mac OS applications, named *Blue Box*.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The OpenStep base of libraries and binary support was termed *Yellow Box*.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Rhapsody evolved into Mac OS X, and the Yellow Box became Cocoa.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Thus, Cocoa classes begin with the letters *NS*, such as NSString or NSArray.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] These stand for the original proprietary term for the OpenStep framework, NeXTSTEP.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Much of the work that went into developing OpenStep was applied to developing Mac OS X, Cocoa being the most visible part.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] For example, NeXTSTEP and OpenStep used Display PostScript for on-screen display of text and graphics, while Cocoa depends on Apple's Quartz (which uses the Portable Document Format (PDF) imaging model, but not its underlying technology).
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa also has a level of World Wide Web support, including the NSURL and WebKit HTML classes, and others, while OpenStep had only rudimentary support for managed network connections via NSFileHandle classes and Berkeley sockets.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The API toolbox was originally called “Yellow Box” and was renamed to Cocoa - a name that had been already trademarked by Apple.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Apple's *Cocoa* trademark had originated as the name of a multimedia project design application for children.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The name was intended to evoke "Java for kids", as it ran embedded in web pages.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The original "Cocoa" program was discontinued following the return of Steve Jobs to Apple.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] At the time, Java was a big focus area for the company, so “Cocoa” was used as the new name for “Yellow Box” because, in addition to the native Objective-C usage, it could also be accessed from Java via a bridging layer.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Even though Apple discontinued support for the Cocoa Java bridge, the name continued and was even used for the Cocoa Touch API.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] One feature of the Cocoa environment is its facility for managing dynamically allocated memory.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Foundation Kit's NSObject class, from which most classes, both vendor and user, are derived, implements a reference counting scheme for memory management.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Objects that derive from the NSObject root class respond to a `retain` and a `release` message, and keep a retain count.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] A method titled `retainCount` exists, but contrary to its name, will usually not return the exact retain count of an object.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] It is mainly used for system-level purposes.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Invoking it manually is not recommended by Apple.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] A newly allocated object created with `alloc` or `copy` has a retain count of one.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Sending that object a `retain` message increments the retain count, while sending it a `release` message decrements the retain count.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] When an object's retain count reaches zero, it is deallocated by a procedure similar to a C++ *destructor*.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] `dealloc` is not guaranteed to be invoked.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Starting with Objective-C 2.0, the Objective-C runtime implemented an optional garbage collector, which is now obsolete and deprecated in favor of Automatic Reference Counting (ARC).
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In this model, the runtime turned Cocoa reference counting operations such as "retain" and "release" into no-ops.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The garbage collector does not exist on the iOS implementation of Objective-C 2.0.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Garbage collection in Objective-C ran on a low-priority background thread, and can halt on Cocoa's user events, with the intention of keeping the user experience responsive.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The legacy garbage collector is still available on Mac OS X version 10.13, but no Apple-provided applications use it.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In 2011, the LLVM compiler introduced Automatic Reference Counting (ARC), which replaces the conventional garbage collector by performing static analysis of Objective-C source code and inserting retain and release messages as necessary.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa consists of three Objective-C object libraries called *frameworks*.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Frameworks are functionally similar to shared libraries, a compiled object that can be dynamically loaded into a program's address space at runtime, but frameworks add associated resources, header files, and documentation.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are implemented as a type of bundle, containing the aforementioned items in standard locations.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] A key part of the Cocoa architecture is its comprehensive views model.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] This is organized along conventional lines for an application framework, but is based on the Portable Document Format (PDF) drawing model provided by Quartz.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] This allows creating custom drawing content using PostScript-like drawing commands, which also allows automatic printer support and so forth.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Since the Cocoa framework manages all the clipping, scrolling, scaling and other chores of drawing graphics, the programmer is freed from implementing basic infrastructure and can concentrate on the unique aspects of an application's content.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The Smalltalk teams at Xerox PARC eventually settled on a design philosophy that led to easy development and high code reuse.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa's design is a fairly, but not absolutely strict application of MVC principles.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Under OpenStep, most of the classes provided were either high-level View classes (in AppKit) or one of a number of relatively low-level model classes like NSString.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Compared to similar MVC systems, OpenStep lacked a strong model layer.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] No stock class represented a "document," for instance.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] During the transition to Cocoa, the model layer was expanded greatly, introducing a number of pre-rolled classes to provide functionality common to desktop applications.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In Mac OS X 10.3, Apple introduced the NSController family of classes, which provide predefined behavior for the controller layer.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] These classes are considered part of the Cocoa Bindings system, which also makes extensive use of protocols such as Key-Value Observing and Key-Value Binding.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The term 'binding' refers to a relationship between two objects, often between a view and a controller.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Bindings allow the developer to focus more on declarative relationships rather than orchestrating fine-grained behavior.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] With the arrival of Mac OS X 10.4, Apple extended this foundation further by introducing the Core Data framework, which standardizes change tracking and persistence in the model layer.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In effect, the framework greatly simplifies the process of making changes to application data, undoing changes when necessary, saving data to disk, and reading it back in.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In providing framework support for all three MVC domains, Apple's goal is to reduce the amount of boilerplate or "glue" code that developers have to write, freeing up resources to spend time on application-specific features.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In most object-oriented languages, calls to methods are represented physically by a pointer to the code in memory.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] This restricts the design of an application since specific *command handling* classes are needed, usually organized according to the chain-of-responsibility pattern.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] While Cocoa retains this approach for the most part, Objective-C's late binding opens up more flexibility.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Under Objective-C, methods are represented by a *selector*, a string describing the method to call.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] When a message is sent, the selector is sent into the Objective-C runtime, matched against a list of available methods, and the method's *implementation* is called.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Since the selector is text data, this lets it be saved to a file, transmitted over a network or between processes, or manipulated in other ways.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The implementation of the method is looked up at runtime, not compile time.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] There is a small performance penalty for this, but late binding allows the same selector to reference different implementations.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] By a similar token, Cocoa provides a pervasive data manipulation method called *key-value coding* (KVC).
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] This allows a piece of data or property of an object to be looked up or changed at runtime by name.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The property name acts as a key to the value.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In traditional languages, this late binding is impossible.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] An object's type need not be known, yet any property of that object can be discovered using KVC.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Also, by extending this system using something Cocoa terms *key-value observing* (KVO), automatic support for undo-redo is provided.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Late static binding is a variant of binding somewhere between static and dynamic binding.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The binding of names before the program is run is called static (*early*); bindings performed as the program runs are dynamic (*late* or *virtual*).
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] One of the most useful features of Cocoa is the powerful *base objects* the system supplies.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] As an example, consider the Foundation classes `NSString` and `NSAttributedString`, which provide Unicode strings, and the `NSText` system in AppKit, which allows the programmer to place string objects in the GUI.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] `NSText` and its related classes are used to display and edit strings.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Paragraph layout can be controlled automatically or by the user, using a built-in "ruler" object that can be attached to any text view.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Spell checking is automatic, using a system-wide set of language dictionaries.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Unlimited undo/redo support is built in.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Using only the built-in features, one can write a text editor application in as few as 10 lines of code.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] With new controller objects, this may fall towards zero.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] When extensions are needed, Cocoa's use of Objective-C makes this a straightforward task.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Objective-C includes the concept of "categories," which allows modifying existing class "in-place".
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Functionality can be accomplished in a category without any changes to the original classes in the framework, or even access to its source.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In other common languages, this same task requires deriving a new subclass supporting the added features, and then replacing all instances of the original class with instances of the new subclass.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The Cocoa frameworks are written in Objective-C.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Cocoa's need for runtime binding means many of Cocoa's key features are not available with Java.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] In 2005, Apple announced that the Java bridge was to be deprecated, meaning that features added to Cocoa in macOS versions later than 10.4 would not be added to the Cocoa-Java programming interface.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] At Apple Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new programming language named Swift, which is intended to replace Objective-C.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Originally, AppleScript Studio could be used to develop simpler Cocoa applications.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] However, as of Snow Leopard, it has been deprecated.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] It was replaced with AppleScriptObjC, which allows programming in AppleScript, while using Cocoa frameworks.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] The Cocoa programming environment can be accessed using other tools with the aid of bridge mechanisms such as PasCocoa, PyObjC, CamelBones, RubyCocoa, and a D/Objective-C Bridge.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] Third-party bindings available for other languages include AppleScript, Clozure CL, Monobjc and NObjective (C#), Cocoa# (CLI), Cocodao and D/Objective-C Bridge, LispWorks, Object Pascal, CamelBones (Perl), PyObjC (Python), FPC PasCocoa (Lazarus and Free Pascal), RubyCocoa (Ruby).
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] A Ruby language implementation named MacRuby, which removes the need for a bridge mechanism, was formerly developed by Apple, while Nu is a Lisp-like language that uses the Objective-C object model directly, and thus can use the Cocoa frameworks without needing a binding.
[src:objective-c/cocoa-api] There are also open source implementations of major parts of the Cocoa framework, such as GNUstep and Cocotron, which allow cross-platform Cocoa application development to target other operating systems, such as Microsoft Windows and Linux.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Objective-C is the primary programming language you use when writing software for OS X and iOS.
[src:objective-c/introduction] It’s a superset of the C programming language and provides object-oriented capabilities and a dynamic runtime.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Objective-C inherits the syntax, primitive types, and flow control statements of C and adds syntax for defining classes and methods.
[src:objective-c/introduction] It also adds language-level support for object graph management and object literals while providing dynamic typing and binding, deferring many responsibilities until runtime.
[src:objective-c/introduction] This document introduces the Objective-C language and offers extensive examples of its use.
[src:objective-c/introduction] You’ll learn how to create your own classes describing custom objects and see how to work with some of the framework classes provided by Cocoa and Cocoa Touch.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Although the framework classes are separate from the language, their use is tightly wound into coding with Objective-C and many language-level features rely on behavior offered by these classes.
[src:objective-c/introduction] When building apps for OS X or iOS, you’ll spend most of your time working with objects.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Those objects are instances of Objective-C classes, some of which are provided for you by Cocoa or Cocoa Touch and some of which you’ll write yourself.
[src:objective-c/introduction] If you’re writing your own class, start by providing a description of the class that details the intended public interface to instances of the class.
[src:objective-c/introduction] This interface includes the public properties to encapsulate relevant data, along with a list of methods.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Method declarations indicate the messages that an object can receive, and include information about the parameters required whenever the method is called.
[src:objective-c/introduction] You’ll also provide a class implementation, which includes the executable code for each method declared in the interface.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Rather than creating an entirely new class to provide minor additional capabilities over an existing class, it’s possible to define a category to add custom behavior to an existing class.
[src:objective-c/introduction] You can use a category to add methods to any class, including classes for which you don’t have the original implementation source code, such as framework classes like `NSString`.
[src:objective-c/introduction] If you do have the original source code for a class, you can use a class extension to add new properties, or modify the attributes of existing properties.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Class extensions are commonly used to hide private behavior for use either within a single source code file, or within the private implementation of a custom framework.
[src:objective-c/introduction] The majority of work in an Objective-C app occurs as a result of objects sending messages to each other.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Often, these messages are defined by the methods declared explicitly in a class interface.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Sometimes, however, it is useful to be able to define a set of related methods that aren’t tied directly to a specific class.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Objective-C uses protocols to define a group of related methods, such as the methods an object might call on its delegate, which are either optional or required.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Any class can indicate that it adopts a protocol, which means that it must also provide implementations for all of the required methods in the protocol.
[src:objective-c/introduction] It’s common in Objective-C to use Cocoa or Cocoa Touch classes to represent values.
[src:objective-c/introduction] The `NSString` class is used for strings of characters, the `NSNumber` class for different types of numbers such as integer or floating point, and the `NSValue` class for other values such as C structures.
[src:objective-c/introduction] You can also use any of the primitive types defined by the C language, such as `int`, `float` or `char`.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Collections are usually represented as instances of one of the collection classes, such as `NSArray`, `NSSet`, or `NSDictionary`, which are each used to collect other Objective-C objects.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Blocks are a language feature introduced to C, Objective-C and C++ to represent a unit of work; they encapsulate a block of code along with captured state, which makes them similar to closures in other programming languages.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Blocks are often used to simplify common tasks such as collection enumeration, sorting and testing.
[src:objective-c/introduction] They also make it easy to schedule tasks for concurrent or asynchronous execution using technologies like Grand Central Dispatch (GCD).
[src:objective-c/introduction] Although Objective-C includes syntax for exception handling, Cocoa and Cocoa Touch use exceptions only for programming errors (such as out of bounds array access), which should be fixed before an app is shipped.
[src:objective-c/introduction] All other errors—including runtime problems such as running out of disk space or not being able to access a web service—are represented by instances of the `NSError` class.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Your app should plan for errors and decide how best to handle them in order to present the best possible user experience when something goes wrong.
[src:objective-c/introduction] When writing Objective-C code, you should keep in mind a number of established coding conventions.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Method names, for example, start with a lowercase letter and use camel case for multiple words; for example, `doSomething` or `doSomethingElse`.
[src:objective-c/introduction] It’s not just the capitalization that’s important, though; you should also make sure that your code is as readable as possible, which means that method names should be expressive, but not too verbose.
[src:objective-c/introduction] In addition, there are a few conventions that are required if you wish to take advantage of language or framework features.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Property accessor methods, for example, must follow strict naming conventions in order to work with technologies like Key-Value Coding (KVC) or Key-Value Observing (KVO).
[src:objective-c/introduction] If you are new to OS X or iOS development, you should read through *Start Developing iOS Apps Today (Retired)* or *Start Developing Mac Apps Today* before reading this document, to get a general overview of the application development process for iOS and OS X.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Additionally, you should become familiar with Xcode before trying to follow the exercises at the end of most chapters in this document.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Xcode is the IDE used to build apps for iOS and OS X; you’ll use it to write your code, design your app's user interface, test your application, and debug any problems.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Although it’s preferable to have some familiarity with C or one of the C-based languages such as Java or C#, this document does include inline examples of basic C language features such as flow control statements.
[src:objective-c/introduction] If you have knowledge of another higher-level programming language, such as Ruby or Python, you should be able to follow the content.
[src:objective-c/introduction] Reasonable coverage is given to general object-oriented programming principles, particularly as they apply in the context of Objective-C, but it is assumed that you have at least a minimal familiarity with basic object-oriented concepts.
[src:objective-c/introduction] If you’re not familiar with these concepts, you should read the relevant chapters in *Concepts in Objective-C Programming*.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM is written in C++ and is designed for compile-time, link-time, and runtime optimization.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The LLVM project started in 2000 at the University of Illinois Urbana–Champaign, under the direction of Vikram Adve and Chris Lattner.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM was originally developed as a research infrastructure to investigate dynamic compilation techniques for static and dynamic programming languages.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM was released under the University of Illinois/NCSA Open Source License, a permissive free software licence.
[src:objective-c/llvm] In 2005, Apple Inc. hired Lattner and formed a team to work on the LLVM system for various uses within Apple's development systems.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM has been an integral part of Apple's Xcode development tools for macOS and iOS since Xcode 4 in 2011.
[src:objective-c/llvm] In 2006, Lattner started working on a new project named Clang.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The combination of the Clang frontend and LLVM backend is named Clang/LLVM or simply Clang.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The name *LLVM* was originally an initialism for *Low Level Virtual Machine*.
[src:objective-c/llvm] However, the LLVM project evolved into an umbrella project that has little relationship to what most current developers think of as a virtual machine.
[src:objective-c/llvm] This made the initialism "confusing" and "inappropriate", and since 2011 LLVM is "officially no longer an acronym", but a brand that applies to the LLVM umbrella project.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The project encompasses the LLVM intermediate representation (IR), the LLVM debugger, the LLVM implementation of the C++ Standard Library (with full support of C++11 and C++14), etc.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM is administered by the LLVM Foundation.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Compiler engineer Tanya Lattner became its president in 2014 and was still president and Executive Director as of November 2025.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The project was originally available under the UIUC license.
[src:objective-c/llvm] After v9.0.0 released in 2019, LLVM relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:objective-c/llvm] As of November 2022 about 400 contributions had not been relicensed.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM can provide the middle layers of a complete compiler system, taking intermediate representation (IR) code from a compiler and emitting an optimized IR.
[src:objective-c/llvm] This new IR can then be converted and linked into machine-dependent assembly language code for a target platform.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM can accept the IR from the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) toolchain, allowing it to be used with a wide array of extant compiler front-ends written for that project.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM can also be built with gcc after version 7.5.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM can also generate relocatable machine code at compile-time or link-time or even binary machine code at runtime.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM supports a language-independent instruction set and type system.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Each instruction is in static single assignment form (SSA), meaning that each variable (called a typed register) is assigned once and then frozen.
[src:objective-c/llvm] This helps simplify the analysis of dependencies among variables.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM allows code to be compiled statically, as it is under the traditional GCC system, or left for late-compiling from the IR to machine code via just-in-time compilation (JIT), similar to Java.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The type system consists of basic types such as integer or floating-point numbers and five derived types: pointers, arrays, vectors, structures, and functions.
[src:objective-c/llvm] A type construct in a concrete language can be represented by combining these basic types in LLVM.
[src:objective-c/llvm] For example, a class in C++ can be represented by a mix of structures, functions and arrays of function pointers.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The LLVM JIT compiler can optimize unneeded static branches out of a program at runtime, and thus is useful for partial evaluation in cases where a program has many options, most of which can easily be determined unneeded in a specific environment.
[src:objective-c/llvm] This feature is used in the OpenGL pipeline of Mac OS X Leopard (v10.5) to provide support for missing hardware features.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Graphics code within the OpenGL stack can be left in intermediate representation and then compiled when run on the target machine.
[src:objective-c/llvm] On systems with high-end graphics processing units (GPUs), the resulting code remains quite thin, passing the instructions on to the GPU with minimal changes.
[src:objective-c/llvm] On systems with low-end GPUs, LLVM will compile optional procedures that run on the local central processing unit (CPU) that emulate instructions that the GPU cannot run internally.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM improved performance on low-end machines using Intel GMA chipsets.
[src:objective-c/llvm] A similar system was developed under the Gallium3D LLVMpipe, and incorporated into the GNOME shell to allow it to run without a proper 3D hardware driver loaded.
[src:objective-c/llvm] In 2011, programs compiled by GCC outperformed those from LLVM by 10%, on average.
[src:objective-c/llvm] In 2013, phoronix reported that LLVM had caught up with GCC, compiling binaries of approximately equal performance.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM has become an umbrella project containing multiple components.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM was originally written to be a replacement for the extant code generator in the GCC stack, and many of the GCC frontends were modified to work with it, resulting in the now-defunct LLVM-GCC suite.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The modifications generally involved a GIMPLE-to-LLVM IR step so that LLVM optimizers and codegen could be used instead of GCC's GIMPLE system.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Apple was a significant user of LLVM-GCC through Xcode 4.x (2013).
[src:objective-c/llvm] This use of the GCC frontend was considered a temporary measure; it became mostly obsolete with Apple's development of Clang, a newer compiler frontend, with a more modern, modular codebase and greater compilation speed, supporting C, C++, and Objective-C.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Support for LLVM-GCC was dropped in Xcode 5.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Primarily supported by Apple, Clang was aimed at replacing the C/Objective-C compiler in the GCC system with a system that is more easily integrated with integrated development environments (IDEs) and has wider support for multithreading.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Support for OpenMP directives has been included in Clang since release 3.8.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Widespread interest in LLVM has led to several efforts to develop new frontends for many other languages, including Ada, D, Delphi, Fortran, Haskell, Julia, Rust, Swift, and others.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The Utrecht Haskell compiler can generate code for LLVM.
[src:objective-c/llvm] While the generator was in early stages of development, in many cases it was more efficient than the C code generator.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) backend uses LLVM and achieves a 30% speed-up of compiled code relative to native code compiling via GHC or C code generation followed by compiling, missing only one of the many optimizing techniques implemented by the GHC.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Many other components are in various stages of development, including, but not limited to, a Java bytecode frontend, a Common Intermediate Language (CIL) frontend, the MacRuby implementation of Ruby 1.9, various frontends for Standard ML, and a new graph coloring register allocator.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The core of LLVM is the intermediate representation (IR), a low-level programming language similar to assembly.
[src:objective-c/llvm] IR is a strongly typed reduced instruction set computer (RISC) instruction set which abstracts away most details of the target.
[src:objective-c/llvm] For example, the calling convention is abstracted through `call` and `ret` instructions with explicit arguments.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Also, instead of a fixed set of registers, IR uses an infinite set of temporaries of the form %0, %1, etc.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM supports three equivalent forms of IR: a human-readable assembly format, an in-memory format suitable for frontends, and a dense bitcode format for serializing.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The many different conventions used and features provided by different targets mean that LLVM cannot truly produce a target-independent IR and retarget it without breaking some established rules.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Examples of target dependence beyond what is explicitly mentioned in the documentation can be found in a 2011 proposal for "wordcode", a fully target-independent variant of LLVM IR intended for online distribution.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The LLVM project also introduces another type of intermediate representation named MLIR which helps build reusable and extensible compiler infrastructure by employing a plugin architecture named Dialect.
[src:objective-c/llvm] It enables the use of higher-level information on the program structure in the process of optimization including polyhedral compilation.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Some features are not available on some platforms.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Most features are present for IA-32, x86-64, z/Architecture, ARM, and PowerPC.
[src:objective-c/llvm] In the past, LLVM also supported other backends, fully or partially, including C backend, Cell SPU, mblaze (MicroBlaze), AMD R600, DEC/Compaq Alpha (Alpha AXP) and Nios2, but that hardware is mostly obsolete, and LLVM developers decided the support and maintenance costs were no longer justified.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM also supports WebAssembly as a target, enabling compiled programs to execute in WebAssembly-enabled environments such as Google Chrome / Chromium, Firefox, Microsoft Edge, Apple Safari or WAVM.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM-compliant WebAssembly compilers typically support mostly unmodified source code written in C, C++, D, Rust, Nim, Kotlin and several other languages.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The LLVM machine code (MC) subproject is LLVM's framework for translating machine instructions between textual forms and machine code.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Formerly, LLVM relied on the system assembler, or one provided by a toolchain, to translate assembly into machine code.
[src:objective-c/llvm] LLVM MC's integrated assembler supports most LLVM targets, including IA-32, x86-64, ARM, and ARM64.
[src:objective-c/llvm] For some targets, including the various MIPS instruction sets, integrated assembly support is usable but still in the beta stage.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The lld subproject is an attempt to develop a built-in, platform-independent linker for LLVM. lld aims to remove dependence on a third-party linker.
[src:objective-c/llvm] As of May 2017, lld supports ELF, PE/COFF, Mach-O, and WebAssembly in descending order of completeness. lld is faster than both flavors of GNU ld.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Unlike the GNU linkers, lld has built-in support for link-time optimization (LTO).
[src:objective-c/llvm] This allows for faster code generation as it bypasses the use of a linker plugin, but on the other hand prohibits interoperability with other flavors of LTO.
[src:objective-c/llvm] The LLVM project includes an implementation of the C++ Standard Library named libc++, dual-licensed under the MIT License and the UIUC license.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Since v9.0.0, it was relicensed to the Apache License 2.0 with LLVM Exceptions.
[src:objective-c/llvm] This implements a suite of cache-locality optimizations as well as auto-parallelism and vectorization using a polyhedral model.
[src:objective-c/llvm] llvm-libc is an incomplete, upcoming, ABI independent C standard library designed by and for the LLVM project.
[src:objective-c/llvm] Due to its permissive license, many vendors release their own tuned forks of LLVM.
[src:objective-c/llvm] This is officially recognized by LLVM's documentation, which suggests against using version numbers in feature checks for this reason.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C programs developed for non-Apple operating systems or that are not dependent on Apple's APIs may also be compiled for any platform supported by GNU, GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) or LLVM/Clang.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C source code "messaging/implementation" program files usually have `.m` filename extensions, while Objective-C "header/interface" files have `.h` extensions, the same as C header files.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C++ files are denoted with a `.mm` filename extension.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C was created mainly by Brad Cox and Tom Love in the early 1980s at their company Productivity Products International (PPI).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Leading up to the creation of their company, both had been introduced to Smalltalk while at ITT Corporation's Programming Technology Center in 1981.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The earliest work on Objective-C traces back to around then.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Cox was intrigued by problems of true reusability in software design and programming.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] He realized that a language like Smalltalk would be invaluable in building development environments for system developers at ITT.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] However, he and Tom Love also recognized that backward compatibility with C was critically important in ITT's telecom engineering milieu.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Cox began writing a pre-processor for C to add some of the abilities of Smalltalk.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] He soon had a working implementation of an object-oriented extension to the C language, which he named Object-Oriented Pre-Compiler (OOPC).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Love was hired by Schlumberger Research in 1982 and had the opportunity to acquire the first commercial copy of Smalltalk-80, which further influenced the development of their brainchild.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] To demonstrate that real progress could be made, Cox showed that making interchangeable software components really needed only a few practical changes to existing tools.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Specifically, they needed to support objects in a flexible manner, come supplied with a usable set of libraries, and allow for the code (and any resources needed by the code) to be bundled into one cross-platform format.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Love and Cox eventually formed PPI to commercialize their product.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] To avoid legal disputes with his previous employers, Cox reimplemented his compiler for the language, which was renamed "Objective-C".
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The company's main product line consisted of this compiler, along with class libraries intended to be used with it.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In 1986, Cox published the main description of Objective-C in its original form in the book *Object-Oriented Programming: An Evolutionary Approach*.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Although he was careful to explain that there is more to the problem of reusability than just what Objective-C provides, the language was often compared feature for feature with other languages.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In 1988, NeXT licensed Objective-C from StepStone (the new name of PPI, the owner of the Objective-C trademark) and extended the GCC compiler to support Objective-C.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] NeXT developed the Application Kit (AppKit) and Foundation Kit libraries on which the NeXTSTEP user interface and Interface Builder were based.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] While the NeXT workstations failed to make a great impact in the marketplace, the tools were widely lauded in the industry.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] NeXT dropped hardware production and focused on software tools, selling NeXTSTEP (and OPENSTEP) as a platform for custom programming.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] To circumvent the terms of the GPL, NeXT had originally intended to ship the Objective-C frontend separately, allowing the user to link it with GCC to produce the compiler executable.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Stallman, this plan was rejected after Stallman consulted with GNU's lawyers and NeXT agreed to make Objective-C part of GCC.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The work to extend GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) was led by Steve Naroff, who joined NeXT from StepStone.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The compiler changes were made available as per GNU General Public License (GPL) terms, but the runtime libraries were not, rendering the open source contribution unusable to the general public.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This led to other parties developing such runtime libraries under open source licenses.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Later, Steve Naroff was also principal contributor to work at Apple to build the Objective-C frontend to Clang.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The GNU project started work on its free software implementation of Cocoa, named GNUstep, based on the OpenStep standard.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Dennis Glatting wrote the first GNU Objective-C runtime in 1992.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The current GNU Objective-C runtime, in use since 1993, is the one developed by Kresten Krab Thorup while he was a university student in Denmark.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Thorup also worked at NeXT from 1993 to 1996.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] After acquiring NeXT in 1996, Apple Computer used OpenStep in its then-new operating system, Mac OS X.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This included Objective-C, NeXT's Objective-C-based developer tool, Project Builder, and its interface design tool, Interface Builder.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Both were later merged into one application, Xcode.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Most of Apple's current Cocoa API is based on OpenStep interface objects and is the most significant Objective-C environment being used for active development.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] At Worldwide Developers Conference (WWDC) 2014, Apple introduced a new language, Swift, which was characterized as "Objective-C without the C".
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C is a thin layer atop C and is a "strict superset" of C, meaning that it is possible to compile any C program with an Objective-C compiler and to freely include C language code within an Objective-C class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C derives its object syntax from Smalltalk.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] All of the syntax for non-object-oriented operations (including primitive variables, pre-processing, expressions, function declarations, and function calls) are identical to those of C, while the syntax for object-oriented features is an implementation of Smalltalk-style messaging.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The Objective-C model of object-oriented programming is based on message passing to object instances.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In Objective-C, one does not *call a method*; one *sends a message*.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This is unlike the Simula-style programming model used by C++.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The difference between these two concepts is in how the code referenced by the method or message name is executed.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In a Simula-style language, the method name is—in most cases—bound to a section of code in the target class by the compiler.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In Smalltalk and Objective-C, the target of a message is resolved at runtime, with the receiving object itself interpreting the message.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A method is identified by a *selector* or `SEL` — a unique identifier for each message name, often just a `NUL`-terminated string representing its name—and resolved to a C method pointer implementing it: an `IMP`.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A consequence of this is that the message-passing system has no type checking.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The object to which the message is directed—the *receiver*—is not guaranteed to respond to a message, and if it does not, it raises an exception.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The "method" call is translated by the compiler to the `objc_msgSend(id self, SEL op, ...)` family of runtime functions.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Different implementations handle modern additions like `super`.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In GNU families, this function is named `objc_msg_sendv`, but it has been deprecated in favor of a modern lookup system under `objc_msg_lookup`.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Both styles of programming have multiple strengths and weaknesses.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Object-oriented programming in the Simula (C++) style allows multiple inheritance and faster execution by using compile-time binding whenever possible, but it does not support dynamic binding by default.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] It also forces all methods to have a corresponding implementation unless they are abstract.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The Smalltalk-style programming as used in Objective-C allows messages to go unimplemented, with the method resolved to its implementation at runtime.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] For example, a message may be sent to a collection of objects, to which only some will be expected to respond, without fear of producing runtime errors.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Message passing also does not require that an object be defined at compile time.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] An implementation is still required for the method to be called in the derived object.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C requires that the interface and implementation of a class be in separately declared code blocks.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] By convention, developers place the interface in a header file and the implementation in a code file.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The header files, normally suffixed .h, are similar to C header files while the implementation (method) files, normally suffixed .m, can be very similar to C code files.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This is analogous to class declarations as used in other object-oriented languages, such as C++ or Python.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The interface of a class is usually defined in a header file.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A common convention is to name the header file after the name of the class, e.g.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] `Ball.h` would contain the interface for the class `Ball`.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the above, plus signs denote class methods, or methods that can be called on the class itself (not on an instance), and minus signs denote instance methods, which can only be called on a particular instance of the class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Class methods also have no access to instance variables.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Note that `instanceMethod2With2Parameters:param2_callName:` demonstrates the interleaving of selector segments with argument expressions, for which there is no direct equivalent in C/C++.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Return types can be any standard C type, a pointer to a generic Objective-C object, a pointer to a specific type of object such as NSArray *, NSImage *, or NSString *, or a pointer to the class to which the method belongs (instancetype).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The default return type is the generic Objective-C type `id`.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Method arguments begin with a name labeling the argument that is part of the method name, followed by a colon followed by the expected argument type in parentheses and the argument name.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A derivative of the interface definition is the *category*, which allows one to add methods to existing classes.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The interface only declares the class interface and not the methods themselves: the actual code is written in the implementation file.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Implementation (method) files normally have the file extension `.m`, which originally signified "messages".
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Methods are written using their interface declarations.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The syntax allows pseudo-naming of arguments.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Internal representations of a method vary between different implementations of Objective-C.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] If myColor is of the class `Color`, instance method `-changeColorToRed:green:blue:` might be internally labeled `_i_Color_changeColorToRed_green_blue`.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The `i` is to refer to an instance method, with the class and then method names appended and colons changed to underscores.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] As the order of parameters is part of the method name, it cannot be changed to suit coding style or expression as with true named parameters.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] However, internal names of the function are rarely used directly.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Generally, messages are converted to function calls defined in the Objective-C runtime library.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] It is not necessarily known at link time which method will be called because the class of the receiver (the object being sent the message) need not be known until runtime.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Once an Objective-C class is written, it can be instantiated.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This is done by first allocating an uninitialized instance of the class (an object) and then by initializing it.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] An object is not fully functional until both steps have been completed.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] These steps should be accomplished with one line of code so that there is never an allocated object that hasn't undergone initialization (and because it is unwise to keep the intermediate result since `-init` can return a different object than that on which it is called).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Also, some classes implement class method initializers.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Like `+new`, they combine `+alloc` and `-init`, but unlike `+new`, they return an autoreleased instance.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The *alloc* message allocates enough memory to hold all the instance variables for an object, sets all the instance variables to zero values, and turns the memory into an instance of the class; at no point during the initialization is the memory an instance of the superclass.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The *init* message performs the set-up of the instance upon creation.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the above example, notice the `id` return type.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This type stands for *pointer to any object* in Objective-C (See the Dynamic typing section).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The initializer pattern is used to assure that the object is properly initialized by its superclass before the init method performs its initialization.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A non-valid object pointer has the value `nil`; conditional statements like `if` treat nil like a null pointer, so the initialization code will not be executed if `[super init]` returned nil.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] If there is an error in initialization, the init method should perform any necessary cleanup, including sending a `release` message to self, and return `nil` to indicate that initialization failed.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Any checking for such errors must only be performed after having called the superclass initialization to ensure that destroying the object will be done correctly.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] If a class has more than one initialization method, only one of them (the *designated initializer*) needs to follow this pattern; others should call the designated initializer instead of the superclass initializer.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In other programming languages, these are called *interfaces*.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C was extended at NeXT to introduce the concept of multiple inheritance of specification, but not implementation, through the introduction of protocols.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This is a pattern achievable either as an abstract multiple inherited base class in C++, or as an *interface* (as in Java and C#).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C makes use of ad hoc protocols called *informal protocols* and compiler-enforced protocols called *formal protocols*.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] An informal protocol is a list of methods that a class can opt to implement.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] It is specified in the documentation, since it has no presence in the language.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Informal protocols are implemented as a category (see below) on NSObject and often include optional methods, which, if implemented, can change the behavior of a class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] For example, a text field class might have a delegate that implements an informal protocol with an optional method for performing auto-completion of user-typed text.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The text field discovers whether the delegate implements that method (via reflective programming (reflection)) and, if so, calls the delegate's method to support the auto-complete feature.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A formal protocol is similar to an interface in Java, C#, and Ada 2005.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] It is a list of methods that any class can declare itself to implement.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C versions before 2.0 required that a class must implement all methods in a protocol it declares itself as adopting; the compiler will emit an error if the class does not implement every method from its declared protocols.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C 2.0 added support for marking certain methods in a protocol optional, and the compiler will not enforce implementation of optional methods.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] A class must be declared to implement that protocol to be said to conform to it.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Formal protocols cannot provide any implementations; they simply assure callers that classes that conform to the protocol will provide implementations.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the NeXT/Apple library, protocols are frequently used by the Distributed Objects system to represent the abilities of an object executing on a remote system.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] denotes that there is the abstract idea of locking.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] instances of NSLock claim that they will provide an implementation for the two instance methods.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C, like Smalltalk, can use dynamic typing: an object can be sent a message that is not specified in its interface.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This can allow for increased flexibility, as it allows an object to "capture" a message and send the message to a different object that can respond to the message appropriately, or likewise send the message on to another object.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This behavior is known as *message forwarding* or *delegation* (see below).
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Alternatively, an error handler can be used in case the message cannot be forwarded.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] If an object does not forward a message, respond to it, or handle an error, then the system will generate a runtime exception.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] If messages are sent to *nil* (the null object pointer), they will be silently ignored or raise a generic exception, depending on compiler options.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Static typing information may also optionally be added to variables.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This information is then checked at compile time.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the following four statements, increasingly specific type information is provided.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The statements are equivalent at runtime, but the extra information allows the compiler to warn the programmer if the passed argument does not match the type specified.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be of any class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* may be an instance of any class that conforms to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In the above statement, *foo* must be an instance of the *NSNumber* class, and it must conform to the *`NSCopying`* protocol.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] In Objective-C, all objects are represented as pointers, and static initialization is not allowed.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The simplest object is the type that id (objc_obj *) points to, which only has an *isa* pointer describing its class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Other types from C, like values and structs, are unchanged because they are not part of the object system.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] This decision differs from the C++ object model, where structs and classes are united.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Objective-C permits the sending of a message to an object that may not respond.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Rather than responding or simply dropping the message, an object can forward the message to an object that can respond.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Forwarding can be used to simplify implementation of certain design patterns, such as the observer pattern or the proxy pattern.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] An object wishing to implement forwarding needs only to override the forwarding method with a new method to define the forwarding behavior.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The action method `performv::` need not be overridden, as this method merely performs an action based on the selector and arguments.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Notice the `SEL` type, which is the type of messages in Objective-C.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] Note: in OpenStep, Cocoa, and GNUstep, the commonly used frameworks of Objective-C, one does not use the `Object` class.
[src:objective-c/objective-c] The `- (void)forwardInvocation:(NSInvocation *)anInvocation` method of the `NSObject` class is used to do forwarding.
